<p valign="top">KILL(2) avr-Xinu KILL(2)</p>

<p style="margin-top: 1em" valign="top"><b>NAME</b></p>

<p style="margin-left:8%;">kill &minus; terminate a
process</p>


<p style="margin-top: 1em" valign="top"><b>SYNOPSIS</b></p>

<p style="margin-left:8%;"><i>int kill(pid) <br>
int pid;</i></p>


<p style="margin-top: 1em" valign="top"><b>DESCRIPTION</b></p>

<p style="margin-left:8%;"><i>Kill</i> will stop process
<i>pid</i> and remove it from the system, returning SYSERR
if the process id is invalid, OK otherwise. <i>Kill</i>
terminates a process immediately. If the process has been
queued on a semaphore, it is removed from the queue and the
semaphore count is incremented as if the process had never
been there. Processes waiting to send a message to a full
port disappear without affecting the port. If the process is
waiting for I/O, the I/O is stopped (if possible).</p>

<p style="margin-left:8%; margin-top: 1em">One can kill a
process in any state, including a suspended one. Once
killed, a process cannot recover.</p>

<p style="margin-top: 1em" valign="top"><b>BUGS</b></p>

<p style="margin-left:8%;">At present there is no way to
recover space allocated dynamically when a process
terminates. However, <i>kill</i> does recover the stack
space allocated to a process when it is created.</p>

<p style="margin-left:8%; margin-top: 1em">XINU V7
February&nbsp;8, 2011 XINU V7</p>
